The Americas
------------
[4] USA (Florida)
Date: Mon 4 May 2015
Source: News Channel 8 [edited]
http://www.wfla.com/story/28974297/measles-cases-reported-in-florida


Measles cases reported in Florida
---------------------------------
Five cases of measles have been reported in Florida during the past month, health officials say. The cases are in St. Lucie and Indian River counties. "We should be concerned in the way that if we see one, that means we could have another one, and from that one we could still keep getting other cases and seeing other people exposed to just one case. It could happen," said Adlin Santiago, RN Specialist at the Health Department in Hillsborough County.

Santiago and other health experts recommend vaccination as the best way for people to protect themselves from the disease, which can be deadly especially for young children. However, pediatrician Dr. Jose Jimenez said once or twice a week parents tell him they don't want their child vaccinated. Usually he's able to convince them to do it -- but not always.

Students are required to have certain vaccinations, including measles, but there are exceptions for religious and medical reasons. Statewide, 93.3 percent of kindergarten students had all required immunizations as of November 2014. In Hillsborough County, 92 percent of kindergartners were vaccinated as of this fall, according to Department of Health data. The rate in Pinellas [County] is 91.3 percent, in Polk [County] it is 96.4 percent and in Pasco [County] it is 95.4 percent.

[Byline: Lauren Mayk]

