[7] UK (South Devon, England)
Date: Thu 7 May 2015
Source: Herald Express [summ., edited]
http://www.torquayheraldexpress.co.uk/Measles-warning-South-Devon-cases-confirmed/story-26458727-detail/story.html


Measles warning for South Devon after 2 cases confirmed
-------------------------------------------------------
Public Health England is advising parents in Devon to ensure their children are fully protected by the MMR (measles, mumps and rubella) vaccine following 2 confirmed cases of measles in children. Letters advising parents to ensure their children are fully protected against measles by having had 2 doses of the MMR vaccine and that measles is circulating in the community has been issued to parents at some local schools.

Two doses of the MMR vaccine offers full protection against the 3 illnesses, provided the 1st dose is given after 12 months of age and the 2nd after 18 months of age. Unless advised otherwise, parents should follow the recommended NHS vaccination schedule. The vaccine may also protect your child if given within 72 hours of exposure to someone with measles. If already infected with measles, the MMR will not cause any harm.

Dr Nick Young, Consultant in Communicable Disease Control (CCDC) for Public Health England in Devon, Cornwall and Somerset, said:

"I'd appeal to any parents who have not yet had their children vaccinated to get them protected as soon as possible through their GP. Children should receive 2 doses of MMR vaccine for maximum protection. MMR not only protects them, but also limits the chances of the virus spreading more widely, for example to children who are too young to have the vaccine and to adults who may be more vulnerable to the disease. It is important to remember that MMR is a highly effective and safe vaccine." Information about the MMR vaccine can be found by visiting http://www.nhs.uk/conditions/vaccinations/pages/mmr-vaccine.aspx.

[Byline: Paul Greaves]

